Source	Segment	Lens / bias	Real signal underneath
Sales	Enterprise buyers (admins)	Anchored on deal-blockers and competitive parity	Need to govern what their org can do
Support	SMB end-users	Selection bias toward people in pain right now	Need to focus without being overwhelmed
Survey	Everyone, low-resolution	Stated preference, socially desirable framing	"Simpler workflows" is a Rorschach test — they project their own pain onto it
These aren't competing answers — they're different jobs.

Enterprise admin job: "When I'm rolling this tool out across my org, I want to control who can do what, so I can satisfy security/compliance and prevent damage." Permissions = safety.
SMB user job: "When I'm just trying to get work done, I want fewer decisions in front of me, so I can focus." Simplicity = speed.
Survey "simpler workflows" is the aggregate emotional residue of both groups, but blurred. It's the lowest-fidelity source you have — treat it as a thermometer, not a diagnosis.
Notice that these two jobs aren't in tension — they're complementary. Strong permissions actually enable simpler workflows: when an admin pre-decides what users can do, the user sees fewer choices and feels less overwhelmed. The enterprise ask and the SMB ask might be two halves of the same product move.

Each source's bias matters:

Sales hears people in active negotiation. Their "wants" are often deal-table positioning, not deeply-held jobs. Discount their requests by ~30% as competitive parity asks.
Support hears people angry enough to file a ticket. Massive selection bias — for every complaint, ~26 silent users had the same friction and just left. The signal is real but the volume is misleading.
Surveys produce stated preferences that drift toward virtuous-sounding answers. Nobody answers "I want more clicks and harder decisions." "Simpler" is what people say when they don't know what they actually want.
