Problem definition (JTBD framing):

When SaaS PMs and contributors push time-sensitive updates and decisions to teammates through the tool, they have no reliable way to know whether the message was received, understood, and absorbed into the recipient's plans — so they end up accountable for outcomes they couldn't actually control, paying for it in missed deadlines, eroded trust, and significant emotional distress.

Pains & Gains breakdown:

Functional pain: comments visually buried; updates indistinguishable from noise
Cognitive pain: persistent low-grade anxiety about whether messages landed
Consequence pain: missed deadlines, missed dependencies, broken commitments
Emotional pain: shame and blame for outcomes outside their control (this is the load-bearing one — it's why people cried)
Functional gain wanted: confidence the message was received and understood
Emotional gain wanted: not be alone in being accountable — once the message lands, the responsibility transfers
Functional job: coordinate work and decisions across asynchronous teammates
Emotional job (the lever): feel that following the process protects you, not exposes you
Social job: preserve trust and reputation when things go wrong
