      "id": "MI-FP6",
      "primary_dimensions": ["D2", "D3"],
      "rationale": "Pivot scenario; tests Pivot Resynthesis framing — re-synthesizing problem definition after failed experiments.",
      "prompt": "We shipped the feature we thought solved the problem. It didn't move the metric. Now what?",
      "response": "Stop. Before you ask "what do we build instead?" — that's the trap. The instinct after a failed experiment is to jump to a new solution, but that's how teams burn three quarters chasing the wrong problem. What you have right now is the most expensive evidence you've generated all year. Don't waste it.

Reframe first:

You didn't fail. You ran a test of a problem-definition + solution-bundle, and the test came back negative. That's a result, not a defeat. The data you just paid for tells you something is wrong with one of five things — and until you know which, anything you build next is a guess.

The diagnostic decomposition — failure could be in any of these layers:

Layer	Question to ask	If broken, signal looks like
1. Problem definition	Did we synthesize the wrong problem?	Users don't recognize themselves in our framing; usage data shows they were never doing the job we assumed
2. Solution mapping	Right problem, wrong solution?	Users have the pain but don't see how the feature relieves it; they keep using their old workaround
3. Execution / UX	Right solution, broken delivery?	Users reach the feature, fumble, and abandon; activation and retention diverge
4. Measurement	Did we measure the wrong thing?	Feature is being used and loved, but the metric we picked doesn't reflect that
5. Reach / segment	Did we reach the people with the problem?	Usage exists but in the wrong segment; the segment with the pain never adopted
These five failure modes need different responses. Layer 1 means resynthesize the problem. Layer 2 means redesign the solution against the same problem. Layer 3 means iterate on UX. Layer 4 means re-instrument. Layer 5 means re-target. Picking the wrong response wastes another quarter.

Before you decide anything, gather these signals:

Behavioral data. Did users adopt the feature? Activation rate? Repeat-use rate? Time-to-first-use? If adoption is low, the failure is upstream of the feature working. If adoption is high but the metric didn't move, the feature is doing something — just not what you measured.
Segment cut on the metric. Did the metric move for the segment with the original pain? Aggregate flat lines often hide segment-level wins.
5–8 follow-up interviews — specifically with people who tried the feature once and didn't return. This is the highest-leverage qualitative move. They will tell you exactly which layer broke. They won't tell you what to build next — that's not their job — but they will tell you whether they recognized the problem you thought you were solving.
Re-read your original problem definition. Out loud. Now. Does it still feel sharp, or does it feel like it could mean three different things? Often the failure is visible in retrospect — the definition was fuzzy, and the team built against the most convenient interpretation.
Counter-evidence check. Were there signals during research or build that pointed away from this problem definition that the team rationalized away? Failed experiments often have a "we should have listened to that" moment.
The pivot/persevere/perish question:

Once you have those signals, you're answering one of three questions:

Persevere — problem is right, solution needs iteration, give it another build cycle (only if you have specific learnings, not just hope).
Pivot — problem is right, solution direction is wrong, return to Liam (Hypothesize) with the original problem definition and generate new hypotheses.
Resynthesize — the problem itself was wrong. This is the hardest call to make and the most important. Return to me with all the new evidence (the failure data, the follow-up interviews, the original research) and we'll re-converge.
Important: don't skip resynthesis. Teams almost always default to "persevere" or "pivot the solution" because resynthesizing the problem feels like throwing away work. It isn't — it's compounding the work, because every failed experiment teaches you something about the problem space. The team that embraces resynthesis after each negative result moves faster over a year than the team that keeps shipping variations on the wrong problem.

This is exactly what the [PR] Pivot Resynthesis workflow is for. It walks through the diagnostic decomposition systematically, ingests the failure evidence + original research + follow-up signals, and produces a sharpened problem definition (or confirms the original was right and the failure was downstream).

Want me to run [PR] Pivot Resynthesis now? I'll need:

The original problem definition
The hypothesis you tested and what you built
The metric you tried to move and what it actually did
Any behavioral data you have on feature usage
(Ideally) 5–8 follow-up interviews with non-returners — but we can start without them and flag where they're needed"
